    .docs-content
      h1 Icons
      p By default Framework7 contains pretty limited set of icons used internally by framework7, such are Back and Bars icons:
      pre
        code.html
          | &lt;i class="icon icon-back"&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
          | &lt;i class="icon icon-bars"&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
      p These couple of icons help to keep consistency in main nav elements between iOS and Material themes.
      h2 Framework7 Icons Font
      p In your app, of course, you may need much more icons to represent your content. For this case we have designed <a href="https://github.com/nolimits4web/Framework7-Icons" target="_blank"><b>Framework7 Icons</b></a> font to be used with <b>iOS theme</b> of Framework7. By default it is not included in Framework7 package and latest version of the font can be downloaded at the <a href="https://github.com/nolimits4web/Framework7-Icons" target="_blank"><b>Framework7 Icons</b></a> repository.
      p For Material theme we highly recommend to use greatly designed <a href="https://material.io/icons/" target="_blank"><b>Material Icons</b></a> font.
      h3 Install font
      ol
        li Download and extract the font pack from the <a href="https://github.com/nolimits4web/Framework7-Icons" target="_blank"><b>Framework7 Icons</b></a> repository
        li Copy the <code>framework7-icons.css</code> to your project
        li Copy the <code>fonts</code> folder to your project
        li Ensure the font urls within <code>framework7-icons.css</code> properly reference the <code>fonts</code> path within your project
        li Include a reference to the <code>framework7-icons.css</code> file where you reference app stylesheets:
          pre
            code.html
              | &lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="path/to/framework7-icons.css"&gt;
      h3 Cheatsheet
      p You can use the following <a href="/icons/" target="_blank"><b>cheatsheet</b></a> to easily find the icon you want to use.
      h3 HTML Example
      p It’s easy to incorporate icons into your web page. Here’s a small example:
      pre
        code.html
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
      p This example uses a typographic feature called <a href="http://alistapart.com/article/the-era-of-symbol-fonts" target="_blank">ligatures</a>, which allows rendering of an icon glyph simply by using its textual name. The replacement is done automatically by the web browser and provides more readable code than the equivalent numeric character reference.
      h3 Styling Icons
      h4 Sizing
      p Framework7 Icons look best at 25px, but if an icon needs to be displayed in an alternative size, just use CSS font-size rule:
      pre
        code.css
          | .size-22 { font-size: 22px }
          | .size-25 { font-size: 25px }
          | .size-29 { font-size: 29px }
          | .size-50 { font-size: 50px }
      pre
        code.html
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons size-22"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons size-25"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons size-29"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons size-50"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
      h4 Coloring
      p Using the icon font allows for easy styling of an icon in any <a href="color-themes.html">default color</a> or custom color.
      pre
        code.css
          | .color-custom { color: #ff0000 }
      pre
        code.html
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons color-red"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons color-yellow"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
          | &lt;i class="f7-icons color-custom"&gt;home&lt;/i&gt;
